    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-10-07T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-10-07T18:00:00-05:00" n="1061"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1061">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.5034 (China) Thrift Corp./34: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-07T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 7, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>15. Your 28, October 5, 1 p.m.<note n="9" xml:id="d1061fn9">Not printed.</note>
                    and 29, October 6, 3 p.m. The Department is doubtful whether American
                    authorities in China could properly refuse to recognize the jurisdictional
                    status of the bank as an American citizen if that question were submitted for
                    judicial determination. However, the question is primarily one for consideration
                    by the Court and if the Judge of the United States Court for China is prepared
                    to maintain in any possible judicial proceeding the position reported in the
                    final paragraph of your telegram 29, August [<hi rend="italic">October</hi>] 6,
                    3 p.m., the Department would not object to your suggested instruction to
                    Harbin.</p>
                <p>The Department realizes the desirability of avoiding participation by American
                    authorities in the bank liquidation, if that course may properly be taken, but,
                    if the Court should ultimately be required to assume jurisdiction, it would seem
                    preferable that jurisdiction be taken immediately and that all possible measures
                    be adopted to effect the quickest and most equitable adjustment of the bank’s
                    affairs.</p>
                <p>The Department is making inquiry of the Governor of Nevada in regard to the
                    validity of the company’s charter and will inform you of his reply.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
